{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "This finding contrasts with results obtained many years ago using standard Monte Carlo event generators PYTHIA and HERWIG [13,14], which were recently confirmed by the CMS collaboration [2].Intrinsic-k T is introduced at the starting evolution scale, µ 0, through integrated PDFs in standard Monte Carlo event generators or through TMDs in the PB Method and CASCADE3.",
    "This is achieved by multiplying the density function at µ 0 by a Gaussian distribution with zero mean and width σ which describes the intrinsic-k T distribution.",
    "Therefore, at the starting scale, there is a component related to the transverse motion, represented by the exponent e -k T σ 2.",
    "The width σ is related to the parameter q s used in the PB Method by the relationship σ = √ 2q s.Recently, the CMS Collaboration obtained results on the dependence of the intrinsic-k T width on the center-of-mass collision energy [2] for PYTHIA (CP5, CP4, and CP3 tunes) and HERWIG (CH3 and CH2 tunes).",
    "These results clearly show the energy dependence of the intrinsic-k T width, where the width increases significantly with the collision energy."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "This finding contrasts with results obtained many years ago using standard Monte Carlo event generators PYTHIA and HERWIG [13,14], which were recently confirmed by the CMS collaboration [2].Intrinsic-k T is introduced at the starting evolution scale, µ 0, through integrated PDFs in standard Monte Carlo event generators or through TMDs in the PB Method and CASCADE3.",
    "The width σ is related to the parameter q s used in the PB Method by the relationship σ = √ 2q s.Recently, the CMS Collaboration obtained results on the dependence of the intrinsic-k T width on the center-of-mass collision energy [2] for PYTHIA (CP5, CP4, and CP3 tunes) and HERWIG (CH3 and CH2 tunes)."
